  <!-- ============================================================
       04 — INVESTMENT THESIS
  ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="thesis">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-number">Section 04</div>
      <div class="section-title">Investment Thesis</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">Why private credit, why sponsor-backed secured lending, and why the structural setup in Draft Horse is the highest-conviction expression of this thesis</div>
      <div class="gold-rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <div class="card card-gold">
        <h3>The Thesis in One Sentence</h3>
        <p>Banks have permanently retreated from middle-market PE lending under Basel III/IV capital constraints; $3.9 trillion in private equity dry powder is sitting idle waiting for flexible credit solutions; and private credit managers who show up with committed capital, deep borrower relationships, and collateral discipline are capturing yield premiums at multi-decade highs — Draft Horse enters this environment with all three advantages already in place.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>The Structural Void Banks Left Behind</h3>
        <p>The Basel III regulatory cycle — implemented progressively from 2010 through full adoption in the mid-2020s — imposed significantly higher risk-weighted capital requirements on bank lending to middle-market and sponsor-backed borrowers. The economics of this lending category became structurally unattractive for regulated banks: the yield compression from competitive pricing, combined with elevated regulatory capital charges, made it mathematically difficult for banks to earn acceptable returns on equity. This was not a cyclical retreat — it was a permanent structural withdrawal driven by regulatory economics that will not reverse.</p>
        <p>The void left by this withdrawal is where private credit has grown from a niche strategy to a $1.7+ trillion asset class in under a decade. The managers who moved into this space earliest — those with existing borrower relationships, deep credit expertise, and institutional-grade operations — captured the most attractive terms and the deepest collateral packages. Draft Horse enters this market not as a latecomer chasing compressed spreads, but as a collateral-disciplined direct lender with an existing $100M deployment relationship already structured and ready to execute.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Why Secured Sponsor-Backed Lending Specifically</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Borrower quality floor:</strong> PE sponsors are institutional operators with structured financials, professional management, and reputational equity at stake. Default carries career consequences for a sponsor, not just financial ones.</li>
            <li><strong>Identifiable collateral:</strong> PE sponsors have specific, owned, appraised assets — not just future cash flows from speculative operations. The Fund lends against what exists, not what is projected.</li>
            <li><strong>UCC-1 enforcement superiority:</strong> Perfected lien gives the Fund legally superior rights to collateral assets in any insolvency scenario — substantially higher recovery than unsecured creditors.</li>
            <li><strong>Relationship monitoring:</strong> Direct sponsor relationship means real-time covenant visibility, no intermediary, and maximum early warning on any credit deterioration.</li>
            <li><strong>No auction dynamics:</strong> Bilateral relationship means no competitive bid process, no broker fees, and no premium paid for deal access.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Why the Draft Horse Structure Is the Best Expression</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Five-layer collateral architecture</strong> versus the industry standard of one or two — exponentially more recovery pathways in any stress scenario</li>
            <li><strong>Dual counterparty equity alignment</strong> — same sponsor holds equity in both the borrowing entity AND the hard asset collateral company. Default is doubly painful for the sponsor.</li>
            <li><strong>Aviation hard assets as terminal collateral</strong> — Gulfstream G550 aircraft are globally marketable, independently appraised, and maintain deep secondary market liquidity regardless of borrower's operating condition</li>
            <li><strong>40% equity stake per jet</strong> — the Fund does not merely lend against aviation assets, it holds economic ownership. Aviation equity generates independent income above and beyond the credit spread.</li>
            <li><strong>Zero-fee model</strong> — the structural incentive to generate more spread, not collect fees, creates superior alignment between GP and LP interests</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-critical">
        <strong>The Core Proposition:</strong> Draft Horse Capital Partners offers qualified institutional investors access to a documented private credit facility — yielding 9% to 17% annually, paid quarterly, secured by five independent collateral layers under perfected UCC-1 and FAA Registry first-priority liens — with no management fee, no carried interest, and principal alignment through GP co-investment. The Fund does not rely on market conditions to generate returns; it relies on a specific, documented, bilateral borrower relationship, a structured collateral package, and a principal who has deployed his own capital alongside investors in private credit since the Fund's predecessor entity began operations.
      </div>

      <div style="background:rgba(201,168,76,0.05);border:1px solid var(--border-dim);border-radius:5px;padding:24px 28px;margin-top:8px;">
        <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.22em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--gold-dim);margin-bottom:12px;font-weight:700;">Institutional Allocator Positioning Notes</div>
        <div class="three-col" style="gap:16px;">
          <div style="background:var(--navy-card);border:1px solid var(--border-dim);border-radius:4px;padding:16px 18px;">
            <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#3b82f6;margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Diversified SWF Allocators</div>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.65;">Draft Horse is positioned as a non-correlated, fixed-income-adjacent income strategy within a multi-asset private credit allocation. The fixed quarterly distribution, 36-month term, and zero fee structure create a clean, predictable cash flow profile suitable for income-oriented sleeves of a diversified portfolio.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="background:var(--navy-card);border:1px solid var(--border-dim);border-radius:4px;padding:16px 18px;">
            <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--gold);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Infrastructure &amp; Real Asset Mandates</div>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.65;">Layer 4 — the G550 charter aviation fleet — constitutes operating aviation infrastructure with contracted revenue, defined maintenance obligations, and quantifiable cash yield. Allocators with real asset or infrastructure mandates have a direct asset-class alignment with Layer 4's collateral profile. The Fund holds both a perfected debt lien and 40% equity in the operating entity.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="background:var(--navy-card);border:1px solid var(--border-dim);border-radius:4px;padding:16px 18px;">
            <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--green);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Private Credit Direct Lending</div>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.65;">For allocators with dedicated direct lending sleeves, Draft Horse is a single-obligor, single-facility vehicle with full collateral visibility — the structural opposite of a diversified CLO or BDC. The monitoring depth and enforcement speed available in a bilateral direct lending relationship are the primary underwriting rationale for the concentrated structure.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-page-notice">Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC — Confidential | For Informational Purposes Only | Not an Offer to Sell Securities</div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================
       05 — MACRO TAILWINDS
  ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="macro">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-number">Section 05</div>
      <div class="section-title">Macro Tailwinds</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">Four structural forces that have made 2024–2027 the most favorable environment for secured private credit in a generation</div>
      <div class="gold-rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <p>Private credit does not operate in a vacuum. The yield premiums available in this asset class are not accidental — they are a direct function of structural forces that have reshaped capital markets over the past decade and show no sign of reversing. Draft Horse is positioned at the intersection of all four of them.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:20px;margin-bottom:24px;">
        <div class="macro-card">
          <div class="macro-card-icon">🏦</div>
          <div class="macro-card-title">Banks Are Out of Middle-Market Lending</div>
          <div class="macro-card-body">
            <p>Post-Basel III/IV, banks face significantly elevated risk-weighted capital requirements on middle-market and sponsor-backed loans. The math is simple and irreversible: a bank holding a $50M middle-market loan must hold more capital against it than ever before, compressing ROE to levels that make the activity economically sub-optimal. Banks are not "retreating" temporarily due to risk aversion — they are repricing the activity out of their business model permanently.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;">The resulting supply-demand imbalance is the foundational reason private credit yields are where they are. When a $10B institutional PE sponsor cannot get a bank to write a competitive middle-market facility, they turn to direct lenders. Direct lenders who have existing relationships and committed capital write the deal at premium rates. Draft Horse has both.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="macro-card">
          <div class="macro-card-icon">📈</div>
          <div class="macro-card-title">Private Credit Is the Fastest-Growing Asset Class on Earth</div>
          <div class="macro-card-body">
            <p>Private credit AUM grew from under $500B in 2012 to over $1.7 trillion in 2024. Current projections from Preqin, BlackRock, and Apollo estimate the asset class will exceed $3.5 trillion by 2028 — driven not by speculation, but by the same structural bank withdrawal that created the initial void. Sovereign wealth funds, pension funds, insurance companies, and endowments are all allocating into private credit in scale for the first time in their institutional history.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;">Global PE dry powder currently stands at approximately $3.9 trillion. Every dollar of that dry powder eventually needs credit solutions to optimize returns. The demand side of private credit is structural, institutional, and growing. Draft Horse enters at a $100M scale against a single existing relationship — not competing for the top of the market, but capturing a specific, high-conviction opportunity within it.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="macro-card">
          <div class="macro-card-icon">✈️</div>
          <div class="macro-card-title">Hard Asset Collateral Values Are Rising</div>
          <div class="macro-card-body">
            <p>The aviation hard assets serving as Draft Horse's Layer 4 collateral — Gulfstream G550 jets — operate in a global secondary market characterized by strong and rising demand. Business aviation activity has recovered fully from COVID-era disruptions, and large-cabin, ultra-long-range aircraft capable of transatlantic operations without refueling are in persistent structural shortage. Pre-owned G550 values have remained resilient because the supply pipeline (production ended in 2012) is fixed.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;">Commercial real estate — the brick-and-mortar component of Layer 2 — is in the early stages of recovery across key Texas markets, where the Fund's PE sponsor operates. Texas has benefited from the largest domestic population influx in the country, with commercial real estate demand following population and corporate relocation patterns. Layer 2 collateral is strengthening, not weakening.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="macro-card">
          <div class="macro-card-icon">🤠</div>
          <div class="macro-card-title">Texas PE Ecosystem: The Fastest-Growing Private Capital Market in the U.S.</div>
          <div class="macro-card-body">
            <p>Texas has emerged as the most significant domestic competitor to New York and California for PE activity, driven by a combination of factors that are structural rather than cyclical: zero state income tax (both corporate and individual), an operator-friendly regulatory environment, a growing concentration of Fortune 500 corporate headquarters (ExxonMobil, AT&amp;T, Charles Schwab, HP, Oracle), and the largest domestic net population gain of any state in the country for four consecutive years.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;">The Draft Horse PE sponsor relationship operates within this ecosystem. Draft Horse is governed under Texas law. The PE platform, the borrower operations, the charter company, and the management entity are all rooted in one of the most economically dynamic and tax-efficient jurisdictions in the world. This is not incidental — it is a deliberate structural choice that reduces regulatory friction and optimizes the economic environment for the Fund's operations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card card-gold">
        <h3>What These Tailwinds Mean for Draft Horse Investors — Concretely</h3>
        <p>When banks retreat from middle-market lending, borrowers pay higher rates to private lenders — and those lenders pass a portion of that premium to investors in the form of elevated fixed yields. The 9%–17% yield tier structure in Draft Horse is not arbitrary — it reflects the genuine spread premium available in the current supply-constrained PE lending market, delivered through a direct relationship that eliminates intermediary friction.</p>
        <p>When private credit AUM grows toward $3.5 trillion, the demand for direct lenders with existing borrower relationships — rather than auction-process participants — becomes more valuable, not less. Draft Horse's existing pipeline is not threatened by the growth of the asset class; it is protected by the exclusivity of the direct relationship.</p>
        <p>When hard asset values rise, the Fund's collateral cushion expands in real terms. A G550 valued at $30–45M is worth more to enforcement than one valued at $20M. Rising Texas commercial real estate values strengthen the Layer 2 position. Macro tailwinds are working for the collateral, not against it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-page-notice">Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC — Confidential | For Informational Purposes Only | Not an Offer to Sell Securities</div>
  </section>

