      <!-- FEE STRUCTURE -->
      <div style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(201,168,76,0.07),rgba(8,12,24,0));border:2px solid var(--gold);border-radius:6px;padding:32px 36px;margin-bottom:24px;">
        <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--gold);font-weight:700;margin-bottom:8px;">Fee Structure</div>
        <div style="font-size:1.45rem;color:var(--gold-light);font-family:'Georgia',serif;margin-bottom:18px;">Zero. None. Fully Transparent.</div>
        <p style="color:var(--text);font-size:14px;line-height:1.75;margin-bottom:20px;">Most private credit funds charge 1–2% annual management fees on committed capital — money you pay whether the fund performs or not — plus 10–20% carried interest on profits. A 1.5% management fee on $100M is $1.5M per year extracted from the fund before a dollar reaches investors. Draft Horse charges none of this. The Fund's economics come exclusively from the spread between what the borrower pays and what investors receive. The incentive structure is simple: generate more spread, not collect more fees.</p>

