  <!-- ============================================================
       07 — FIVE-LAYER COLLATERAL ARCHITECTURE
  ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="collateral">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-number">Section 07</div>
      <div class="section-title">Five-Layer Collateral Architecture</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">This is not typical private credit. Five independent, separately enforceable collateral positions under a single UCC-1 framework.</div>
      <div class="gold-rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <div class="callout-critical">
        <strong>"Five Layers of Downside Protection — This Is Not Typical Private Credit"</strong><br><br>
        Most private credit funds have one collateral layer — operating cash flows, or a real estate mortgage, or a stock pledge. Some have two. Draft Horse has five, each independently enforceable, each covering different asset classes with different liquidity profiles and different legal enforcement pathways. The Fund does not need all five to succeed. The Fund needs exactly one layer to hold in a default scenario to recover principal in full. The other four are structural redundancy that no other single-mandate fund at this scale has bothered to build.
      </div>

      <!-- LAYER STACK -->
      <div class="layer-stack" style="margin:28px 0;">

        <div class="layer-item layer-1">
          <div class="layer-badge">Layer 1 — First Strike</div>
          <div class="layer-title">PE Portfolio Company Cash Flows</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> A perfected assignment of all cash flow rights and receivables generated by the PE sponsor's operating portfolio companies. Under UCC §9-607, upon a default event, the Fund delivers written notice to all of the borrower's account debtors — the entities that owe money to the borrower — redirecting all outstanding and future payments directly to the Fund.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why it's powerful:</strong> Cash flow enforcement is the fastest-acting tool in the collateral package. It does not require physical seizure of assets, court intervention, or complex sale processes. The Fund intercepts income at the source, within 30–60 days of acceleration. This layer is the "first strike" in any enforcement scenario — it generates immediate cash and preserves the Fund's liquidity while longer-duration asset enforcement proceeds in parallel.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Monitoring:</strong> Cash flows are monitored on an ongoing basis through fund administration and direct borrower reporting covenants. Any material deviation from projected cash flow triggers a covenant review prior to any payment default.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="text-align:center;padding:6px 0;color:var(--border);font-size:20px;">↓</div>

        <div class="layer-item layer-2">
          <div class="layer-badge">Layer 2 — Physical Asset Base</div>
          <div class="layer-title">Brick-and-Mortar Real Estate &amp; Inventory</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> UCC-1 perfected security interest against all tangible physical assets of the PE sponsor's portfolio companies — commercial and operational real estate, business inventory, equipment, fixtures, and all physical property. This encompasses every physical asset the borrower owns, from the buildings they operate in to the inventory stacked in their warehouses.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why it's powerful:</strong> Physical assets are independent of operating performance. Even if cash flows compress due to a business cycle, the real estate and inventory have standalone appraised values that do not move in direct correlation to EBITDA. In a Texas commercial real estate market that is actively appreciating due to corporate relocation and population growth, this layer's value is increasing over the term of the loan, not decreasing.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Enforcement:</strong> Under UCC §9-610, the Fund may arrange commercially reasonable public or private disposition of encumbered inventory and personal property. Real estate disposition proceeds apply against principal and accrued interest.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="text-align:center;padding:6px 0;color:var(--border);font-size:20px;">↓</div>

        <div class="layer-item layer-3">
          <div class="layer-badge">Layer 3 — Control Override</div>
          <div class="layer-title">100% Portfolio Company Equity Pledge</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> A pledge of 100% of the PE sponsor's equity interests in all portfolio company holdings. In a default event, the Fund does not merely claim against assets from the outside — the Fund steps into ownership control of the operating businesses themselves. This is the nuclear enforcement option: the Fund becomes the operator, with full authority to manage, restructure, or dispose of the underlying businesses in its entirety.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why it's powerful:</strong> Most private credit funds get a lien against assets. Draft Horse gets ownership rights. If the PE sponsor defaults and the operating businesses are healthy — generating cash, holding valuable assets — the Fund can take control, continue operations, and extract full value over time rather than forcing a distressed fire sale. The equity pledge is a recovery-maximizing tool, not merely an enforcement mechanism.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Practical note:</strong> Exercise of equity pledge rights is coordinated by SCALE LLP and complies with applicable securities law governing transfer of privately-held equity interests. This layer is reserved for use when Layers 1 and 2 alone are insufficient to satisfy the outstanding obligation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="text-align:center;padding:6px 0;color:var(--border);font-size:20px;">↓</div>

        <div class="layer-item layer-4">
          <div class="layer-badge">Layer 4 — Hard Asset Terminal Value</div>
          <div class="layer-title">Gulfstream G550 Aviation Fleet — UCC-1 &amp; FAA Registry Perfected First Lien</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> A perfected first-priority security interest in a fleet of Gulfstream G550 large-cabin, ultra-long-range business jets operated by the charter company in which the PE sponsor holds equity. Security perfection is achieved through dual-filing: (i) UCC-1 financing statement under Article 9 of the Uniform Commercial Code in the applicable state of the debtor's organization, and (ii) conveyance notation on the FAA Civil Aviation Registry in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, pursuant to 49 U.S.C. § 44107 and 14 C.F.R. Part 49 — the federal filing that governs priority of interests in U.S.-registered civil aircraft. For international operational contexts, the Fund's counsel evaluates applicability of the Cape Town Convention (Aircraft Protocol) as an additional layer of international priority protection. Each aircraft is independently appraised prior to lien filing. Each aircraft generates $2.1M–$3.1M in net profit annually from commercial charter operations. Dark Horse holds 40% equity per aircraft — a direct economic ownership stake yielding $840K–$1.24M per jet annually. Target fleet: 24 aircraft. At full build-out, aviation equity income alone generates $20.2M–$29.8M per year.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why it's powerful — secondary market liquidity:</strong> Gulfstream G550 aircraft are among the most globally liquid categories of physical collateral in private credit. Each aircraft — independently appraised in the current range of $30–45M — can be marketed to qualified institutional buyers across the United States, Europe, the Middle East, and Asia-Pacific through established remarketing intermediaries (including AVPRO, jetAVIVA, and comparable institutional brokers) with demonstrated transaction execution timelines of 60–180 days under normal market conditions. The aircraft is physically mobile — it can be repositioned to the most advantageous sale market at the Fund's direction. Unlike fixed real estate or privately-held equity interests, the G550 secondary market has deep buyer pools in multiple jurisdictions and a transparent, observable pricing benchmark.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Income preservation during enforcement:</strong> In an enforcement scenario, charter operations continue generating revenue from the aircraft while the remarketing process proceeds. The Fund exercises its pledge rights over the charter company equity simultaneously — placing a court-appointed receiver over charter operations if necessary — preserving the aircraft's income-generating capacity and maintaining asset condition and maintenance currency during the remarketing period. An aircraft that is operationally current, maintained, and revenue-generating commands a materially higher market price than one that has been grounded.</p>
            <div style="background:rgba(201,168,76,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.25);border-radius:4px;padding:14px 18px;margin-top:14px;">
              <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.18em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--gold);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Note for Infrastructure-Mandate Allocators</div>
              <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;">The Gulfstream G550 charter fleet constitutes <strong>operating aviation infrastructure</strong> — a revenue-generating real asset business with contracted utilization, defined maintenance obligations, and a quantifiable income stream. For sovereign and institutional allocators whose mandate includes infrastructure, real assets, logistics, or transportation, Layer 4 represents an identifiable infrastructure asset position embedded within a secured credit structure. The Fund holds both a senior perfected debt claim against the aircraft (lien) and a 40% equity ownership stake in the operating entity — providing dual exposure to the asset class. The Middle East and Asia-Pacific business aviation market, in particular, has demonstrated strong and rising charter demand from corporate and government users, supporting the income and asset value assumptions underpinning this layer.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="background:rgba(201,168,76,0.07);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:4px;padding:14px 18px;margin-top:12px;">
              <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--gold);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Aviation Equity Economics — Target 24-Jet Fleet</div>
              <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(4,1fr);gap:12px;text-align:center;">
                <div><div style="font-size:18px;color:var(--gold);font-family:'Georgia',serif;">$30–45M</div><div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;color:var(--text-muted);letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-top:4px;">Appraised Value Per Aircraft</div></div>
                <div><div style="font-size:18px;color:var(--gold);font-family:'Georgia',serif;">40%</div><div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;color:var(--text-muted);letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-top:4px;">Dark Horse Equity Per Jet</div></div>
                <div><div style="font-size:18px;color:var(--gold);font-family:'Georgia',serif;">$840K–$1.24M</div><div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;color:var(--text-muted);letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-top:4px;">Annual Income Share Per Jet</div></div>
                <div><div style="font-size:18px;color:var(--gold);font-family:'Georgia',serif;">$20.2–$29.8M</div><div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;color:var(--text-muted);letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-top:4px;">Target Annual Aviation Income (24 Jets)</div></div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="text-align:center;padding:6px 0;color:var(--border);font-size:20px;">↓</div>

        <div class="layer-item layer-5">
          <div class="layer-badge">Layer 5 — The Alignment Lock — Dual Equity Counterparty</div>
          <div class="layer-title">PE Sponsor Guaranty — Both Sides of the Transaction</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> The PE sponsor provides a personal or entity guaranty against the credit facility. But the extraordinary fact here — the structural differentiator that no other single-mandate fund in this market can replicate — is that this same PE sponsor co-owns the charter company that operates the aircraft serving as Layer 4 collateral. The sponsor holds equity on BOTH sides of the transaction: as the primary borrowing entity AND as a co-owner of the hard asset collateral vehicle.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why this is extraordinary:</strong> In a default scenario, the PE sponsor faces impairment from two independent directions simultaneously. Their borrowing entity is in default — damaging their creditworthiness, their investor relationships, and their professional reputation. Their charter company equity — a separately valuable, operating business asset — is subject to enforcement. The sponsor's financial self-interest in preventing default is doubled by this structure. They are not a counterparty who faces credit consequences alone. They face credit consequences AND the loss of a separately held, income-generating hard asset business in which they have meaningful personal equity.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Guaranty Terms:</strong> The PE sponsor guaranty is a full-recourse, continuing guaranty covering all principal, accrued interest, and enforcement costs outstanding under the credit facility. The guaranty survives any bankruptcy, insolvency, or restructuring of the primary borrowing entity. Carve-outs are limited to fraudulent conveyance and are consistent with market-standard exceptions in institutional private credit guaranty documentation. Guarantor financial statements and net worth verification are provided under NDA. SCALE LLP confirms guaranty enforceability and proper execution prior to initial capital close.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>The structural implication:</strong> Layer 5 is not merely a guaranty. It is a structural alignment mechanism that makes the sponsor's financial incentive to perform perfectly consistent with the Fund's incentive to be repaid. This level of counterparty alignment — the same entity having equity exposure on both the liability side and the hard asset collateral side — is exceptionally rare in middle-market private credit. It exists here because the relationship was structured directly, bilaterally, without intermediary, by a principal who thought carefully about what alignment actually looks like in practice.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>


      <div class="card" style="border:2px solid var(--gold);background:linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(201,168,76,0.05) 0%,rgba(8,12,24,0) 70%);margin-bottom:24px;">
        <h3>Collateral Coverage Analysis — Loan-to-Value and Debt Service Framework</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom:14px;">Institutional credit investors require explicit collateral coverage metrics. The following analysis presents the Fund's structural position against the $100M credit facility using the mid-point of appraised collateral value ranges. These figures are illustrative at fund capacity and are based on the target 24-aircraft fleet build-out and current pre-appraisal estimates. Binding appraisals are provided under NDA at the appropriate stage of due diligence.</p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Collateral Layer</th>
              <th>Asset Class</th>
              <th>Estimated Value Range</th>
              <th>Coverage Against $100M Facility</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="td-gold">Layer 1</td>
              <td>PE Portfolio Company Cash Flows</td>
              <td>Borrower-specific (disclosed under NDA)</td>
              <td>Minimum 1.25x DSCR covenant required</td>
              <td>Debt Service Coverage Ratio monitored quarterly; minimum covenant triggers cure period</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="td-gold">Layer 2</td>
              <td>Commercial Real Estate &amp; Inventory</td>
              <td>Disclosed under NDA (Texas portfolio)</td>
              <td>Independent appraisal required prior to close</td>
              <td>Mortgages and UCC-1 on real and personal property; appraiser to be confirmed by SCALE LLP</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="td-gold">Layer 3</td>
              <td>Portfolio Company Equity (100%)</td>
              <td>Implied by business enterprise value</td>
              <td>Pledged via executed equity pledge agreements</td>
              <td>Pledge agreement structure confirmed by SCALE LLP; transfer restrictions reviewed for each entity</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="td-highlight">
              <td class="td-gold">Layer 4</td>
              <td>Gulfstream G550 Aviation Fleet (24 jets target)</td>
              <td>$30M–$45M per aircraft</td>
              <td>$720M–$1.08B at full fleet (7.2x–10.8x facility)</td>
              <td>FAA Civil Aviation Registry; Cape Town Convention where applicable; 40% Dark Horse equity; current fleet count disclosed under NDA</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="td-gold">Layer 5</td>
              <td>PE Sponsor Guaranty (Full Recourse)</td>
              <td>Guarantor financials disclosed under NDA</td>
              <td>Full principal + accrued interest</td>
              <td>Full-recourse continuing guaranty; carved out only for fraud; dual equity exposure (borrower entity + charter company)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="callout" style="margin-top:16px;">
          <strong>Key Metric — Layer 4 Aviation Coverage Alone:</strong> At the target 24-aircraft fleet, the independently appraised mid-point value ($37.5M/aircraft × 24 = $900M) represents a 9.0x coverage ratio against the $100M credit facility. Layer 4 alone — at the low end of the appraisal range ($30M × 24 = $720M) — provides 7.2x coverage. This does not include Layers 1, 2, 3, or 5. Current fleet composition and individual aircraft appraisals are available to qualified investors under NDA.
        </div>
        <div class="info-box" style="margin-top:12px;">
          <strong>Important:</strong> Appraised values are point-in-time estimates. Realizable recovery values in a distressed enforcement scenario may be materially lower than appraised values. The 24-aircraft target represents a build-out over the Fund term; current fleet size and individual aircraft registration details are provided under NDA at the due diligence stage. Layer 1 DSCR and Layer 2 real estate appraisals will be provided in the confidential diligence package.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card card-gold">
        <h3>The Five-Layer Framework: What Needs to Go Wrong for Investors to Lose Principal</h3>
        <p>Every sophisticated allocator's first question about a concentrated private credit fund is: "What has to go wrong for us to lose money?" In Draft Horse, the answer requires a specific, sequential analysis:</p>
        <br>
        <p><strong>For investors to lose principal in Draft Horse, all of the following must occur simultaneously:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Layer 1 fails: The PE sponsor's portfolio company cash flows collapse completely — not reduce, but collapse — to zero, AND</li>
          <li>Layer 2 fails: The commercial real estate and inventory have zero recoverable value in disposition, AND</li>
          <li>Layer 3 fails: The portfolio company equity, which the Fund could take over and operate, has no value whatsoever, AND</li>
          <li>Layer 4 fails: Multiple Gulfstream G550 jets — each independently appraised at $30–45M, each with an active global secondary market — simultaneously become unsaleable, AND</li>
          <li>Layer 5 fails: The PE sponsor's personal guaranty, backed by their equity position in a separately operated charter company, is also worthless.</li>
        </ul>
        <br>
        <p>The probability of total loss across all five layers simultaneously is, under any scenario analysis the Fund has conducted, materially lower than the probability of total loss in a single-collateral private credit structure — not because any of the five layers is risk-free, but because they represent five distinct asset classes with low correlation to one another in stress scenarios. Aviation hard asset values are not directly correlated to PE operating business performance. Commercial real estate valuations move independently of EBITDA cycles. Portfolio company equity may be impaired and still have positive enterprise value recoverable through a controlled wind-down. The structure was designed so that each layer is independently enforceable and independently recoverable, and so that impairment in one layer does not automatically transfer to the others. Investors should review the full risk disclosures in Section 11 and in the PPM for a complete analysis. The five-layer structure reduces but does not eliminate the risk of principal loss.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Collateral Monitoring &amp; Covenant Framework</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom:14px;">Institutional investors require explicit covenant structures and reporting obligations. Draft Horse's Credit Agreement imposes the following monitoring requirements on the borrower:</p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Covenant / Reporting Requirement</th>
              <th>Frequency</th>
              <th>Threshold / Trigger</th>
              <th>Consequence of Breach</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)</td>
              <td>Quarterly</td>
              <td>Minimum 1.25x (EBITDA / annual debt service)</td>
              <td>30-day cure period; then acceleration event</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Financial Statement Delivery</td>
              <td>Quarterly (management); Annual (audited)</td>
              <td>Within 45 days of quarter-end; 90 days of year-end</td>
              <td>Default notice after 10-day cure; acceleration rights</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>UCC-1 / FAA Lien Priority Confirmation</td>
              <td>Annual</td>
              <td>No competing lien of equal or superior priority</td>
              <td>Immediate acceleration right; cure not available</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Material Adverse Change (MAC) Notification</td>
              <td>Immediate upon occurrence</td>
              <td>Any event causing &gt;10% deterioration in enterprise value</td>
              <td>Covenant review; potential acceleration</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Aircraft Appraisal Refresh</td>
              <td>Annual (Layer 4)</td>
              <td>Each aircraft appraised by AVAC or equivalent</td>
              <td>Margin call / additional collateral required if coverage drops below 3.0x</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Insurance Maintenance</td>
              <td>Continuous</td>
              <td>Aircraft hull &amp; liability; property; D&amp;O</td>
              <td>Default notice; Fund has right to insure and charge borrower</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>No Additional Senior Indebtedness</td>
              <td>Continuous negative covenant</td>
              <td>No debt senior to or pari passu with Fund lien without consent</td>
              <td>Immediate acceleration right; cure not available</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="info-box">
          Covenant compliance monitoring is the responsibility of the Fund's Principal with reporting provided through NAV Fund Services. Investors receive a quarterly report summarizing covenant status, collateral position, and distribution detail. Annual audited financial statements include a covenant compliance certificate. Full credit agreement terms are available under NDA.
        </div>
      </div>

    <div class="section-page-notice">Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC — Confidential | For Informational Purposes Only | Not an Offer to Sell Securities</div>
  </section>

