  <!-- ============================================================
       09 — COMPETITIVE DIFFERENTIATION
  ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="competitive">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-number">Section 09</div>
      <div class="section-title">Competitive Differentiation</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">Draft Horse versus investment-grade bonds, high-yield bonds, BDCs, and typical PE funds — an honest institutional-grade comparison that acknowledges trade-offs directly</div>
      <div class="gold-rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <div class="card card-gold">
        <h3>The Honest Comparison — Where Draft Horse Wins and Where It Doesn't</h3>
        <p>Any credible institutional analysis must acknowledge trade-offs honestly. Draft Horse wins on yield, fees, collateral protection, income frequency, and fee structure. It does not win on liquidity — investors are locked for 36 months with no early redemption. Sophisticated allocators understand this trade-off clearly: the yield premium exists <em>because of</em> the liquidity constraint. The 36-month lock is the source of the yield, not a cost of it. The comparison table below presents this trade-off in full.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- MAIN COMPARISON TABLE -->
      <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin-bottom:24px;">
        <table style="min-width:800px;">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Characteristic</th>
