        </div>
      </div>

    <div class="section-page-notice">Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC — Confidential | For Informational Purposes Only | Not an Offer to Sell Securities</div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================
       11 — RISK FACTORS
  ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="risk">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-number">Section 11</div>
      <div class="section-title">Risk Factors</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">Twelve institutional-grade risk disclosures — material, honest, and balanced. Read completely before investing.</div>
      <div class="gold-rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom:28px;">
        <strong>Important:</strong> The following risk factors represent material risks associated with an investment in Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC. This is not an exhaustive list. Prospective investors must review the complete risk disclosures in the Fund's Private Placement Memorandum prepared by SCALE LLP before making any investment decision. Investing in this Fund involves substantial risk, including the possible loss of all principal invested.
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>01 — Illiquidity and Lock-Up Risk</h4>
        <p>Interests in Draft Horse Capital Partners are highly illiquid. There is no secondary market for Fund interests, and none is expected to develop. Investors are subject to a 36-month lock-up with no early redemption rights under any circumstances. Investors must be able to hold an illiquid position for the full 36-month term and should not commit funds they may require for liquidity, emergency, or other purposes during that period. The absence of redemption rights is a material, intentional structural feature — not a temporary restriction — and is fully reflected in the yield premium offered.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>02 — Borrower Default and Credit Risk</h4>
        <p>The Fund's return is dependent on the PE sponsor borrower meeting payment obligations in full and on time. If the borrower defaults, the Fund must initiate enforcement proceedings against collateral — a process that may be time-consuming, costly, and may not result in full recovery of principal and accrued interest. The value of collateral at the time of enforcement may be less than the outstanding loan balance. Borrower financial condition may deteriorate due to factors outside the Fund's control, including macroeconomic developments, operational disruptions, management failures, or competitive pressure.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>03 — Single-Borrower Concentration Risk — The Most Material Risk in This Fund</h4>
        <p>The Fund's deployment is concentrated entirely in a single borrower relationship. This is the most material risk in Draft Horse Capital Partners and should be evaluated carefully and completely by every prospective investor before committing capital. The credit risk is not diversified across counterparties — all exposure is to a single obligor. Any material adverse change in the borrower's financial condition, operating performance, management continuity, legal status, regulatory standing, or industry environment could impair the Fund's ability to recover principal and accrued interest in full, regardless of the breadth of the collateral framework. In a severe stress scenario, correlation between the values of different collateral layers held against a single enterprise is likely to be higher than diversified portfolio analysis would suggest — operating business impairment tends to reduce both cash flow and real asset values simultaneously, compressing the multi-layer recovery cushion in precisely the scenario where it is most needed.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:12px;"><strong>Why concentration is also a structural feature:</strong> The single-borrower structure is a deliberate underwriting philosophy, not a default of capital formation. Direct bilateral lending to a known, evaluated counterparty enables monitoring depth, covenant responsiveness, and enforcement speed that are structurally unavailable in diversified portfolios. Against a single borrower, the Fund maintains real-time visibility into operations, cash flows, material events, and covenant compliance — with no intermediary, no syndicate agent, and no information delay. In broadly syndicated credit facilities with 30+ lenders, material adverse changes are frequently identified only after they have become defaults. In a direct bilateral facility, the Fund is the only creditor at the table and has both the contractual right and the operational relationship to act immediately on any deterioration signal. The concentration risk is real and material. So is the monitoring advantage it enables. Both must be weighed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>04 — Collateral Valuation and Enforcement Risk</h4>
        <p>The value of collateral assets — including real property, business assets, inventory, portfolio company equity, and aviation assets — may be worth materially less at the time of enforcement than estimated at origination. Collateral appraisals are point-in-time estimates and do not guarantee realizable values in a distressed or accelerated sale scenario. Even where the Fund holds a perfected UCC-1 first-priority lien, enforcement may involve time delays, legal costs, borrower contestation, and potential bankruptcy proceedings that temporarily halt or complicate recovery actions. There is no guarantee that enforcement will recover the full outstanding principal and accrued interest.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>05 — Aviation Asset Risk</h4>
        <p>Gulfstream G550 aircraft serving as Layer 4 collateral are subject to risks specific to aviation assets, including FAA and international airworthiness requirements, maintenance cost variability, operational certification requirements, and market cycles in business aviation. Aircraft values may decline materially if demand for large-cabin business jets softens, if new competitive aircraft models compress valuations, or if the borrower's charter operations generate negative publicity or FAA enforcement action. If aircraft are located outside the United States during an enforcement event, repossession may require compliance with international aviation law and multi-jurisdictional legal processes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>06 — Key Person Risk</h4>
        <p>The Fund's investment strategy, borrower relationship, and collateral management are substantially dependent on the judgment, expertise, and continued involvement of Principal Caleb Caraway. The Fund's pipeline originated through a direct, personal relationship that cannot be easily transferred or replicated by a successor. If the Principal were to become unable or unwilling to continue in his capacity, the Fund's ability to manage existing investments, enforce against collateral in a workout scenario, and originate additional deployment opportunities could be materially impaired. The Fund does not currently maintain key person insurance. There can be no assurance that a suitable successor with equivalent borrower access could be identified in a timely manner.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>07 — Regulatory and Compliance Risk</h4>
        <p>The Fund operates under Regulation D Rule 506(c) and §3(c)(1) of the Investment Company Act of 1940. The §3(c)(1) exclusion limits the Fund to 100 beneficial owners — a hard statutory cap that restricts AUM growth beyond the level achievable with 100 investors. Changes in securities laws, regulations, or SEC/FINRA enforcement priorities could affect the Fund's ability to raise capital, maintain its exemptions, or operate as currently structured. Failure to maintain the 506(c) accredited investor verification process — including incomplete verification of any single investor — could subject the Fund to regulatory sanction and potential loss of the Regulation D exemption.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>08 — New Fund and Limited Operating History Risk</h4>
        <p>Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC was formed in February 2026 and has no operating history as a standalone fund vehicle. The Fund has not yet deployed capital, made distributions, navigated a credit deterioration, managed a covenant breach, or executed a workout or enforcement action. While the Principal brings a documented track record from Corinthian Capital Partners and related private credit operations, Draft Horse itself has no performance history. Service providers, operational systems, and governance procedures are newly established and untested under adverse conditions. Investors should not rely solely on the performance history of related entities as a predictor of Draft Horse's future results.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>09 — No Guarantee of Target Yields or Return of Principal</h4>
        <p>The tiered yield structure represents target returns and is not guaranteed. Distributions are contingent on borrower performance and Fund cash flow. The Fund may not achieve its target yields in any given period and may not make distributions in any given quarter. The 100% principal return at maturity is a Fund obligation subject to the borrower's ability to repay and the Fund's ability to enforce against collateral. Principal is not insured, government-guaranteed, or protected by any third-party guarantee. Past performance of Corinthian Capital Partners or any related strategy does not guarantee future results for Draft Horse Capital Partners.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>10 — Tax, Reporting, and Sovereign Investor Considerations</h4>
        <p>An investment in Draft Horse Capital Partners may have complex and potentially adverse tax implications. Fund distributions may be treated as ordinary income to investors, subject to the highest applicable federal and state income tax rates. Pass-through entity tax treatment, potential Unrelated Business Taxable Income (UBTI) considerations for tax-exempt investors, state and local tax obligations in multiple jurisdictions, and the treatment of return-of-capital components in distributions all require individualized tax analysis. The Fund's tax adviser, Spicer Jeffries LLP, serves the Fund — not individual investors.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Sovereign investor-specific note:</strong> Sovereign wealth funds and government-affiliated institutional investors may be entitled to exemption from U.S. federal income tax on certain types of income under Section 892 of the Internal Revenue Code. Whether the Fund's income qualifies for Section 892 treatment depends on the specific nature of the income, the investor's sovereign status, and the applicable facts and law at the time of distribution. Section 892 exemptions do not extend to income that constitutes UBTI or income from certain commercial activities. Sovereign investors should obtain specific tax counsel on the U.S. federal and state tax treatment of their investment in Draft Horse Capital Partners before committing capital. The Fund makes no representation regarding the tax treatment of distributions to sovereign or foreign investors.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>11 — Conflicts of Interest</h4>
        <p>The Principal serves simultaneously as managing partner of multiple investment entities within the Dark Horse platform, including Corinthian Capital Partners and Quarter Horse Capital Partners, which have overlapping mandates and competing demands for management time, attention, and deal flow allocation. The Fund does not currently have an independent advisory board, audit committee, or investor representative body. The Principal is the sole decision-maker on all investment, operational, and governance matters. These structural characteristics create potential conflicts of interest that cannot be fully mitigated by disclosure alone. Investors have limited contractual rights to influence Fund management decisions and no veto rights over individual transactions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <h4>12 — Macroeconomic and Interest Rate Risk</h4>
        <p>While the Fund's private credit structure eliminates direct mark-to-market exposure, the broader macroeconomic environment materially affects the Fund's risk profile in several ways. A prolonged economic downturn could simultaneously impair borrower cash flows and reduce collateral values — compressing recovery prospects in a default scenario precisely when enforcement is most critical. Rising interest rates reduce the relative attractiveness of the Fund's fixed yield to prospective investors in future periods and may affect the borrower's ability to service debt at the contracted rate. Geopolitical events, commodity price shocks, or systemic credit events could affect the business aviation market, commercial real estate valuations, or PE sponsor portfolio performance in ways that the Fund's collateral protections cannot fully offset.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

      <div class="card card-gold" style="margin-top:24px;">
        <h3>Scenario Analysis — Three Stress Cases and Fund Response</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom:18px;">Institutional investors require forward-looking scenario analysis. The following three scenarios illustrate the Fund's structural response to progressively severe stress conditions. These are not projections of expected outcomes — they are stress-case illustrations of how the collateral architecture functions under adverse conditions.</p>

        <div class="two-col" style="gap:16px;margin-bottom:16px;">
          <div style="background:rgba(34,197,94,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(34,197,94,0.2);border-radius:4px;padding:18px 20px;">
            <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--green);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Base Case — Borrower Performs</div>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Assumption:</strong> PE sponsor meets all debt service obligations on schedule. DSCR ≥ 1.5x throughout facility term. Aviation fleet operates at 70%+ utilization.</p>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;"><strong>Fund Outcome:</strong> Full quarterly distributions to investors at contracted tier rate. Aviation equity income of $20.2M–$29.8M/year (at 24-jet build-out) supplements Fund GP economics. 100% principal returned at 36-month maturity. All five collateral layers remain unexercised.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="background:rgba(251,191,36,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(251,191,36,0.2);border-radius:4px;padding:18px 20px;">
            <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Stress Case — Partial Cash Flow Impairment</div>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Assumption:</strong> Borrower experiences 30–40% EBITDA compression due to macroeconomic downturn. DSCR falls toward minimum 1.25x covenant. No default, but elevated monitoring.</p>
            <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;"><strong>Fund Response:</strong> Covenant review triggered. Cure period activates. Fund may require additional collateral or principal paydown. If resolved within cure period, no distribution interruption. If not resolved: Layer 1 enforcement (cash flow sweep to Fund) begins. Distributions continue from swept cash flows. Layers 2–5 remain unexercised as backstop.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="background:rgba(248,113,113,0.07);border:1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.2);border-radius:4px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:16px;">
          <div style="font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--red);margin-bottom:8px;font-weight:700;">Severe Stress Case — Borrower Default, Full Enforcement</div>
          <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Assumption:</strong> PE sponsor cannot service debt. DSCR falls below 1.0x. Acceleration event declared. Full enforcement initiated.</p>
          <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Layer 1 Action:</strong> Cash flow sweep via UCC §9-607 notice to account debtors — begins within 30–60 days of acceleration. Captures any remaining operating revenue.</p>
          <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>Layer 4 Action (Aviation — Primary Recovery Vehicle):</strong> FAA Registry and Cape Town Convention enforcement initiated. At current per-aircraft market value of $30M–$45M, a sale of even 4–5 aircraft from the fleet would generate $120M–$225M against the $100M facility — sufficient for full principal recovery with interest, before Layers 1, 2, 3, and 5 contribute a single dollar. Aviation assets are globally marketable within 60–180 days under normal secondary market conditions.</p>
          <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text);line-height:1.7;"><strong>Principal Impairment Threshold:</strong> For investors to experience a principal loss in this scenario, the following must all occur simultaneously: (a) no operating cash flows are swept, AND (b) all real estate and inventory dispositions yield zero recovery, AND (c) portfolio company equity has zero enterprise value, AND (d) G550 aircraft are entirely unsaleable in the global market, AND (e) guarantor is insolvent with zero recoverable assets. The probability of this simultaneous multi-layer failure is assessed as extremely remote under any plausible economic scenario.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-box">
          <strong>Disclosure:</strong> Scenario analyses are illustrative only. They are not projections of expected outcomes and do not constitute a guarantee of any return or principal protection. Actual recovery in an enforcement scenario depends on facts and circumstances at the time, including asset values, legal costs, timing, and market conditions. Investors should conduct independent scenario analysis with their own advisors.
        </div>
      </div>

    <div class="section-page-notice">Draft Horse Capital Partners LLC — Confidential | For Informational Purposes Only | Not an Offer to Sell Securities</div>
  </section>

